Since $\overrightarrow{P}$ lies on the perpendicular bisector of $\overline{AB},$
\[\overrightarrow{P} - \frac{\overrightarrow{A} + \overrightarrow{B}}{2}\]is orthogonal to $\overrightarrow{B} - \overrightarrow{A}.$  Hence,
\[\left( \overrightarrow{P} - \frac{\overrightarrow{A} + \overrightarrow{B}}{2} \right) \cdot (\overrightarrow{B} - \overrightarrow{A}) = 0.\]Expanding, we get
\[\overrightarrow{P} \cdot (\overrightarrow{B} - \overrightarrow{A}) - \frac{\overrightarrow{A} + \overrightarrow{B}}{2} \cdot (\overrightarrow{B} - \overrightarrow{A}) = 0.\]Then
\[\overrightarrow{P} \cdot (\overrightarrow{B} - \overrightarrow{A}) = \frac{\overrightarrow{A} + \overrightarrow{B}}{2} \cdot (\overrightarrow{B} - \overrightarrow{A}) = \frac{1}{2} (\overrightarrow{B} \cdot \overrightarrow{B} - \overrightarrow{A} \cdot \overrightarrow{A}).\]Similarly, since $\overrightarrow{P}$ lies on the perpendicular bisector of $\overline{CD},$
\[\overrightarrow{P} \cdot (\overrightarrow{D} - \overrightarrow{C}) = \frac{1}{2} (\overrightarrow{D} \cdot \overrightarrow{D} - \overrightarrow{C} \cdot \overrightarrow{C}).\]Let $\overrightarrow{P} = a \overrightarrow{A} + b \overrightarrow{B} + c \overrightarrow{C} + d \overrightarrow{D}.$  Then
\begin{align*}
\overrightarrow{P} \cdot (\overrightarrow{B} - \overrightarrow{A}) &= (a \overrightarrow{A} + b \overrightarrow{B} + c \overrightarrow{C} + d \overrightarrow{D}) \cdot (\overrightarrow{B} - \overrightarrow{A}) \\
&= b \overrightarrow{B} \cdot \overrightarrow{B} + (a - b) \overrightarrow{A} \cdot \overrightarrow{B} + c \overrightarrow{C} \cdot \overrightarrow{B} + d \overrightarrow{D} \cdot \overrightarrow{B} \\
&\quad - a \overrightarrow{A} \cdot \overrightarrow{A} - (a - b) \overrightarrow{A} \cdot \overrightarrow{B} - c \overrightarrow{A} \cdot \overrightarrow{C} - d \overrightarrow{A} \cdot \overrightarrow{D} \\
&= b \overrightarrow{B} \cdot \overrightarrow{B} - a \overrightarrow{A} \cdot \overrightarrow{A} + c \overrightarrow{C} \cdot \overrightarrow{B} + d \overrightarrow{D} \cdot \overrightarrow{B} - c \overrightarrow{A} \cdot \overrightarrow{C} - d \overrightarrow{A} \cdot \overrightarrow{D}.
\end{align*}Also,
\begin{align*}
\overrightarrow{P} \cdot (\overrightarrow{D} - \overrightarrow{C}) &= (a \overrightarrow{A} + b \overrightarrow{B} + c \overrightarrow{C} + d \overrightarrow{D}) \cdot (\overrightarrow{D} - \overrightarrow{C}) \\
&= d \overrightarrow{D} \cdot \overrightarrow{D} + (c - d) \overrightarrow{C} \cdot \overrightarrow{D} + a \overrightarrow{A} \cdot \overrightarrow{D} + b \overrightarrow{B} \cdot \overrightarrow{D} \\
&\quad - c \overrightarrow{C} \cdot \overrightarrow{C} - (c - d) \overrightarrow{C} \cdot \overrightarrow{D} - a \overrightarrow{A} \cdot \overrightarrow{C} - b \overrightarrow{B} \cdot \overrightarrow{C} \\
&= d \overrightarrow{D} \cdot \overrightarrow{D} - c \overrightarrow{C} \cdot \overrightarrow{C} + a \overrightarrow{A} \cdot \overrightarrow{D} + b \overrightarrow{B} \cdot \overrightarrow{D} - a \overrightarrow{A} \cdot \overrightarrow{C} - b \overrightarrow{B} \cdot \overrightarrow{C}.
\end{align*}Since $\overrightarrow{A},$ $\overrightarrow{B},$ $\overrightarrow{C},$ and $\overrightarrow{D}$ lie on a circle, $\overrightarrow{A} \cdot \overrightarrow{A} = \overrightarrow{B} \cdot \overrightarrow{B} = \overrightarrow{C} \cdot \overrightarrow{C} = \overrightarrow{D} \cdot \overrightarrow{D}.$  Hence,
\begin{align*}
b \overrightarrow{B} \cdot \overrightarrow{B} - a \overrightarrow{A} \cdot \overrightarrow{A} + c \overrightarrow{C} \cdot \overrightarrow{B} + d \overrightarrow{D} \cdot \overrightarrow{B} - c \overrightarrow{A} \cdot \overrightarrow{C} - d \overrightarrow{A} \cdot \overrightarrow{D} &= d \overrightarrow{D} \cdot \overrightarrow{D} - c \overrightarrow{C} \cdot \overrightarrow{C} + a \overrightarrow{A} \cdot \overrightarrow{D} + b \overrightarrow{B} \cdot \overrightarrow{D} - a \overrightarrow{A} \cdot \overrightarrow{C} - b \overrightarrow{B} \cdot \overrightarrow{C} \\
\Rightarrow \qquad c \overrightarrow{C} \cdot \overrightarrow{B} + d \overrightarrow{D} \cdot \overrightarrow{B} - c \overrightarrow{A} \cdot \overrightarrow{C} - d \overrightarrow{A} \cdot \overrightarrow{D} &= a \overrightarrow{A} \cdot \overrightarrow{D} + b \overrightarrow{B} \cdot \overrightarrow{D} - a \overrightarrow{A} \cdot \overrightarrow{C} - b \overrightarrow{B} \cdot \overrightarrow{C} \\
\Rightarrow \qquad (c - a) \overrightarrow{A} \cdot \overrightarrow{C} + (d - b) \overrightarrow{B} \cdot \overrightarrow{C} + (b - d) \overrightarrow{B} \cdot \overrightarrow{D} + (a - c) \overrightarrow{A} \cdot \overrightarrow{D} &= 0.
\end{align*}The vectors $\overrightarrow{A},$ $\overrightarrow{B},$ $\overrightarrow{C},$ and $\overrightarrow{D}$ are not collinear, so the coefficients of $\overrightarrow{A} \cdot \overrightarrow{C},$ $\overrightarrow{B} \cdot \overrightarrow{C},$ $\overrightarrow{B} \cdot \overrightarrow{D},$ and $\overrightarrow{A} \cdot \overrightarrow{D}$ must all be 0.  This means $a = c$ and $b = d.$

We can repeat the same argument with any other pair of perpendicular bisectors.  For example, the perpendicular bisectors of $\overline{BC}$ and $\overline{AD}$ give us $b = d$ and $a = c.$  Thus, $a = b = c = d.$  Then
\[\overrightarrow{P} = a \overrightarrow{A} + a \overrightarrow{B} + a \overrightarrow{C} + a \overrightarrow{D} = a (\overrightarrow{A} + \overrightarrow{B} + \overrightarrow{C} + \overrightarrow{D}).\]Since $\overrightarrow{P}$ is the midpoint of $\overrightarrow{A} + \overrightarrow{B} + \overrightarrow{C} + \overrightarrow{D},$ $a = \frac{1}{2}.$  Hence, $a + b + c + d = 2,$ so the answer is $\boxed{2}.$

